io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection

Interface Bijection<A,B>

  • Type Parameters:
    A - The type of objects in the first set of this bijection
    B - The type of objects in the second set of this bijection
    All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractBijection, MapBackedBijection

    public interface Bijection<A,B>
extends Iterable<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
    A custom Collection that represents a bijective mapping.

    A Bijection maps two sets of objects in a 1:1 mapping. For more information on bijections, check out https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bijection.

    Since:
    2.0.0
    Version:
    June 29, 2021
    Author:

      • contains

        boolean contains(@NotNull
                 A obj1,
                 @NotNull
                 B obj2)
        Returns whether or not this Bijection contains the specified mapping.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        contains(new Pairing<>(obj1, obj2))}
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.
        Parameters:
        obj1 - The first element of the pairing
        obj2 - The second element of the pairing
        Returns:
        Whether or not this pair is mapped together in the bijection
        See Also:
        contains(Pairing)

      • add

        boolean add(@NotNull
            @NotNull Bijection.Pairing<A,B> pairing)
        Adds the specified Pairing to this Bijection, if possible.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        add(pairing.getFirst(), pairing.getSecond())
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.

        This method returns false regardless of whether the method failed due to the defined pairing existing or due to conflicts with other existing pairings. For a method that throws an exception if the new pairing conflicts, use addOrFail(Pairing), or alternatively use contains(Pairing) to see if the addition failed due to the pairing already existing.

        Parameters:
        pairing - The pairing to add
        Returns:
        Whether or not this Bijection was modified by this method
        See Also:
        add(Object, Object), addOrFail(Pairing)

      • addOrFail

        boolean addOrFail(@NotNull
                  A obj1,
                  @NotNull
                  B obj2)
        Adds the specified pairing to this Bijection, if possible.

        This method completes successfully if and only if the pairing does not conflict with any already existing pairings in the bijection. If this is the case, then this method is identical to add(Object, Object). However, if this new pairing does conflict with a pre-existing pairing, then this method throws an IllegalBijectiveStateException instead.

        Parameters:
        obj1 - The first element of the pairing
        obj2 - The second element of the pairing
        Returns:
        Whether or not this Bijection was modified by this method
        Throws:
        IllegalBijectiveStateException - If the addition failed due to conflicts with pre-existing pairings
        See Also:
        add(Pairing), IllegalBijectiveStateException.failedPairingAddition(io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection.Bijection.Pairing<?, ?>)

      • to2DArray

        @NotNull
@NotNull Object[][] to2DArray(boolean makeRowsPairwise)
        Returns this bijection as a 2D array.

        If the argument makeRowsPairwise is true, then the returned 2D array will have dimensions Nx2, where N is the number of mappings in this bijection. Each of the N rows of the array will correspond to a unique mapping of this Bijection.

        If the argument makeRowsPairwise is false, then the returned 2D array will have dimensions 2xN, where N is the number of mappings in this bijection. This will essentially be an array of the two arrays returned by toArrayPair().

        Parameters:
        makeRowsPairwise - Whether to return an Nx2 or 2xN array
        Returns:
        This Bijection as a 2D array
        See Also:
        toArrayPair()

      • makeUnmodifiable

        @NotNull
static <X,Y> @NotNull Bijection<X,Y> makeUnmodifiable(@NotNull
                                                               @NotNull Bijection<X,Y> bijection)
        Returns an unmodifiable Bijection backed by the given Bijection.

        Changes in the original bijection will be reflected in the newly returned copy.

        Type Parameters:
        X - The type of elements in the first set of the bijections (see the A parameter for Bijection)
        Y - The type of elements in the second set of the bijections (see the B parameter for Bijection)
        Parameters:
        bijection - The bijection to wrap with an unmodifiability layer
        Returns:
        An unmodifiable copy of the given Bijection backed by the original bijection
